default3.  What should the BBC be for and whatdefault 
defaultshould be the purpose of public service broadcasting?default&#xa0;defaultPublic service broadcasting refers to TV programmes that are
default broadcast for the public benefit rather than for purely commercial purposes.
default (Ofcom)
defaultOfcom measures delivery of programming by public service broadcasters
default against four objectives, or "public service purposes": 
default(a) informing our understanding of the world
default; 
default(b) stimulating knowledge and learning
default(c) reflecting UK cultural identity; and 
default(d) representing diversity and alternative viewpoints.
default 
defaultVLV supports these criteria of measurement and believes they are still fit for purpose. 
default4.  What is the BBC for?defaultWhile commercial broadcasters aim to return value to their shareholders or owners, the BBC exists to create public value. In other words, it aims to serve its audiences not just as consumers, but as members of a wider society,
default with programmes and services which, while seeking to inform, 
defaulteducate and entertain audiences, also serve wider public purposes. Public value is a measure of the BBC’s contribution to the quality of life in the UK. 
